Actually, let me re-read the ensure_run_started function:

```rust
fn ensure_run_started() {
    if !RUN_STARTED.with(|c| c.get()) {
        record(
            EventType::RunStarted,
            Actor::Harness,
            json!({"retroactive": true, "reason": "run_completed_without_start"}),
        );
        RUN_STARTED.with(|c| c.set(true));
    }
}
```

It calls `record()` and then sets RUN_STARTED. So if we call `ensure_run_started()` from within `record()`, and ensure_run_started calls record() again, then the second call to record() would check RUN_STARTED again - but RUN_STARTED is still false (it's set AFTER the record call in ensure_run_started). So it would call ensure_run_started again. Infinite recursion.

The fix: set RUN_STARTED before calling record() in ensure_run_started:

```rust
fn ensure_run_started() {
    if !RUN_STARTED.with(|c| c.get()) {
        RUN_STARTED.with(|c| c.set(true));  // Set BEFORE calling record()
        record(
            EventType::RunStarted,
            Actor::Harness,
            json!({"retroactive": true, "reason": "run_completed_without_start"}),
        );
    }
}
```

Then we can call `ensure_run_started()` at the top of `record()`. When ensure_run_started calls record() for RunStarted, the re-entrant call to record() would see RUN_STARTED=true and skip ensure_run_started. No infinite recursion!

